{"title_page": "Somali wild donkey", "text_new": "{{subspeciesbox\n| name = Somali wild ass\n| image = Somali Wild Ass.JPG\n| image_caption =\n| status = CR\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/7949/0|title=''Equus africanus''|author=Moehlman, P.D.|author2=Yohannes, H.|author3=Teclai, R.|author4=Kebede, F.|last-author-amp=yes|year=2008|access-date=20 May 2014|ref=harv}} Assessment includes information on conservation status of two recognised subspecies.</ref>\n| genus = Equus\n| species = africanus\n| species_link = African wild ass\n| subspecies = somaliensis\n| authority = ([[Theodor Noack|Noack]], 1884)<ref>{{in lang|de}} Noack, Th. (1884). \"Neues aus der Tierhandlung von Karl Hagenbeck, sowie aus dem Zoologischen Garten in [[Hamburg]]\". ''Der Zoologische Garten'' '''25''': 100-115.</ref>\n| synonyms_ref = <ref name=\"Groves 2007\">Groves, C.P., & Smeenk, C. (June 2007). \"The nomenclature of the African wild ass\". ''[[Zoologische Mededelingen]]'' '''81'''(1). [http://www.zoologischemededelingen.nl/81/nr01/a06 HTM], [http://www.zoologischemededelingen.nl/cgi/t/text/get-pdf?c=zoomed;idno=8101a06 PDF]</ref>\n| synonyms =\n* ''Asinus taeniopus'' var. ''Somaliensis'' Noack, 1884\n* ''Equus asinus somalicus'' [[Philip Sclater|Sclater]], 1884<ref>[[Philip Sclater|Sclater, P.L.]] (1884). \"On some mammals from Somali-land\". ''Proceedings of the Scientific Meetings of the [[Zoological Society of London]]'' '''1884''': 538-542, pls. 49-50.</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''Somali wild donkey''' (''Equus africanus somaliensis'')<ref name=\"Groves 2007\"/>, also known as a ''Somali wild ass''' is a [[subspecies]] of the [[African wild donkey]].\n\nIt is found in [[Somalia]], the [[Southern Red Sea]] region of [[Eritrea]], and the [[Afar Region]] of [[Ethiopia]]. The legs of the Somali wild donkey are striped, resembling those of its relative, the [[zebra]].\n\n==Current distribution and habitat==\nThere are likely fewer than 1,000 animals (or even 700) in the wild<ref>{{cite web\n  |url=http://www.stlzoo.org/about/contact/pressroom/zoointhenews/somaliwildassproblem/\n  |author=Bonner, Jeffrey\n  |date=June 1, 2008\n  |title=What's the Zoo to do with its Somali wild ass problem?\n  |publisher=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]] & [[Saint Louis Zoo]]\n  |accessdate=12 April 2017}}</ref> and the ''[[International Union for Conservation of Nature|IUCN]] Red List of endangered species'' described it as \"critically endangered\". This means they face an extremely high risk of extinction in the wild.\n\nA few hundred specimens live in [[Somalia]], [[Eritrea]] and [[Ethiopia]].<ref name=\"Somali\">{{cite web\n  |url=http://www.zoobasel.ch/de/aktuell/detail.php?NEWSID=413&apm=1_4&nof\n  |title=Seltene Sch\u00f6nheit - Somali-Wildeselfohlen bezaubert das Zolli-Publikum\n  |date=16 December 2010\n  |publisher=[[Zoo Basel]]\n  |accessdate=12 April 2017\n  |language=de}}</ref>\n\n==Reproduction==\nSomali wild donkeyss typically give birth in the spring, a common characteristic among equids, after a year-long gestation. Within hours, the foal is up on its legs and keeping up with its mother. At around five-days-old, the foal is already nibbling grass. By the time its two-weeks old, the foal is grazing regularly, however, still depending on its mother's milk for fluids. The foal is weaned by 12 to 14 months, but still stays close to its mother, only leaving to play or feed with the other foals in the herd.\n\n==Behavior==\nDue to the limited resources found in their habitat, Somali wild donkeys live in a fission-fusion society. Most adults live alone, but sometimes form small herds consisting of females and their young. In areas that have more resources, or have more rain, they will sometimes fuse together to form larger temporary herds.\nStallions can maintain territories as large as nine square miles. They frequently leave dung piles as markers to remind them of their territory's boundaries. While females are welcome in their territories, stallions will often fight other males who try to mate with females in their territories. However, stallions have been observed allowing males into their territories for grazing, as long as they show no interest in his harem. <ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://zoonooz.sandiegozoo.org/zoonooz/somali-wild-ass/|title=Somali Wild Ass|first=Wendy|last=Perkins|date=5 June 2017|website=ZOONOOZ}}</ref>\n\n==Captivity==\n\n===Global population===\n{{As of|2011}}, there are about 200 individuals in captivity around the globe<ref name=\"Somali\"/> living in 34 [[zoo]]s, as well as three animals (as of 2009) in the [[Yotvata Hai-Bar Nature Reserve]] in [[Israel]], to the north of [[Eilat]].<ref name=\"Stamm\">{{cite web| url=http://www.wst-foundation.ch/wcms/wsts.cfm/h,29/s,22/c,0/sc,de/blue.htm| title=Somali-Wildesel ''(Equus africanus somalicus)''| work=F\u00f6rderprojekte der Werner Stamm Stiftung| publisher=Werner Stamm Stiftung| accessdate=2011-11-14|language=de}}</ref>  The international [[studbook]] is managed by [[Tierpark Berlin]].<ref name=\"Direktoren\">{{cite web| url=http://www.zoodirektoren.de/index.php?option=com_k2&view=item&id=179:somali-wildesel-equus-africanus-somalicus&Itemid=255| title=Somali-Wildesel| publisher=[[Verband Deutscher Zoodirektoren]]| accessdate=22 May 2014|language=de}}</ref>\n\n===Zoo Basel===\n[[File:ZolliWildAss.JPG|thumb|Somali Wild Ass at [[Zoo Basel]]]]\nThe leading zoo for breeding this rare donkey is [[Zoo Basel]], Switzerland. Its [[Breeding programs at Zoo Basel|breeding program]] manages the [[Europe]]an studbook for the Somali wild donkey and coordinates the [[European Endangered Species Programme]] (EEP)<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.zoobasel.ch/aktuell/detail.php?NEWSID=187&PHPSESSID=34277fba68d5857ecdb43ae645c9831c%7CZoo | title=INDIAN RHINO VISION (IRV) 2020| date=8 May 2008| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120315234046/http://www.zoobasel.ch/aktuell/detail.php?NEWSID=187&PHPSESSID=34277fba68d5857ecdb43ae645c9831c%7CZoo| archivedate=15 March 2012| publisher=[[Zoo Basel]]| accessdate=22 May 2014|language=de}}</ref> \u2013 as well as the global species committee of the Somali wild donkey since 2004.<ref name=\"Stamm\" />\n\nZoo Basel started keeping Somali wild donkeys in 1970 and had its first birth in 1972.  Since then, 11 stallions and 24 females (as of 2009) were born and survived childhood.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.zoobasel.ch/de/aktuell/detail.php?NEWSID=140&apm=1_4&nof| title=Zweites Somali-Wildeselfohlen im Zolli geboren | date=27 December 2007| publisher=[[Zoo Basel]]| accessdate=22 May 2014|language=de}}</ref> Today, all Somali wild donkeys in captivity are related to the original group at Zoo Basel.<ref name=\"Direktoren\"/>\n\nAs of January 18, 2012, there are four Somali wild donkeys in Basel: The stallion \"Gigolo\" (3) and three females (among them \"Yogala\"-14).<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.zoobasel.com/en/aktuell/detail.php?NEWSID=499&apm=1_4&nof| title=Dance of the Somali wild asses| date=18 January 2012| publisher=[[Zoo Basel]]|accessdate=22 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n===France===\nSince 1987, the [[R\u00e9serve Africaine de Sigean]], in the south of [[France]], has had a number of Somali wild donkeys, with births occurring regularly, including two on June 30, 2010 and March 29, 2013.<ref>{{cite web\n  |url=http://archives-lepost.huffingtonpost.fr/article/2010/07/07/2143765_naissance-rare-au-zoo-de-sigean-un-ane-de-somalie.html\n  |title=Naissance rare au zoo de Sigean: un \u00e2ne de Somalie!\n  |publisher=[[Le Huffington Post]] (French-language edition of the [[Huffington Post]])\n  |date=July 7, 2010\n  |language=fr\n  |accessdate= 12 April 2017\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n  |url=http://www.ladepeche.fr/article/2013/04/27/1615575-une-naissance-tres-rare-a-la-reserve-de-sigean.html\n  |title=Une naissance tr\u00e8s rare \u00e0 la R\u00e9serve de Sigean\n  |publisher=[[La D\u00e9p\u00eache du Midi]]\n  |date=April 27, 2013\n  |language=fr\n  |accessdate= 12 April 2017\n}}</ref>\n\n===United States===\nOnly four institutions breed the Somali wild donkey in the [[United States]]:<ref name=\"whiteoak\">{{cite web| url=http://www.whiteoakwildlife.org/animal-programs/somali-wild-ass/| title=Somali Wild Ass| work=Animal Programs| publisher=[[White Oak Conservation|White Oak]]| accessdate=22 May 2014 }}</ref> [[Dallas Zoo]], [[St. Louis Zoo]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Somali wild ass born at St. Louis Zoo|url=http://www.connecttristates.com/news/story.aspx?id=125173#.UcSpdo4rV8s|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|accessdate=21 June 2013}}</ref> [[San Diego Zoo Safari Park]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Three Somali Wild Ass Foals Born At San Diego Zoo Safari Park|url=http://media.sandiegozoo.org/2011/07/13/three-somali-wild-ass-foals-born-at-san-diego-zoo-safari-park/|publisher=San Diego Zoo|accessdate=21 June 2013}}</ref> and [[White Oak Conservation]] in [[Yulee, Florida]].<ref name=\"whiteoak\"/> White Oak received a herd in 2008 as part of an international effort to save Somali wild donkey from extinction. Since then, the herd has produced 18 [[foals]], including several born in spring 2013.<ref name=\"whiteoak\"/> The Dallas Zoo has just had two Somali wild donkey foals, both female, one born July 9 and the other on July 19, 2017.  The St. Louis Zoo's most recent birth was on July 30, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stlzoo.org/about/contact/pressroom/pressreleases/somali-wild-ass-foal-born-july-30-2019|title=Somali wild ass foal born July 30, 2019|date=27 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe San Diego Zoo Safari Park is home to eleven Somali wild donkeys, the largest population of Somali wild donkeys in North America. The park received its first herd from the Basel Zoo in 1981. Their first foal was born in 1986. Since then, 49 foals have been born, the most recent being a female born on March 17, 2018. San Diego Zoo Global also works to help save this endangered species in the wild. <ref name=\"auto\"/> <ref>{{cite web|url=http://zoonooz.sandiegozoo.org/2018/04/12/somali-wild-ass-foal-explores-habitat/|title=Somali Wild Ass Foal Explores Habitat|first=Public|last=Relations|date=12 April 2018|website=ZOONOOZ}}</ref>\n\n===Domestication===\n[[File:Somali wild ass pair.jpg|thumb|right|Two Somali wild donkeys at [[Marwell Wildlife|Marwell Zoo]]]]\nDomestic [[donkey]]s found in [[Italy]] are typically descended from the Somali wild donkey, as opposed to those from other European countries where domesticated stock are usually descended from the [[Nubian wild donkey]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/cambridgeshire/hi/people_and_places/history/newsid_9150000/9150180.stm|title=Pompeii Horse Is in Fact an Ass|date=3 November 2010|publisher = [[BBC]]}}</ref>{{Citation needed|date=September 2014|reason=This statement is not exactly what the source says: \"Italian donkeys are typically descended from the Somali wild ass\" is not exactly the same as what the source says, which is that those donkeys which are derived from the Somali wild ass are typically found in Italy (the former implies all Italian donkeys, but the latter may be talking about only a few of the Italian donkeys).  But in any case, we need a direct ref for this, not just a local BBC report which does not give its own refs.}}\n\n==Conservation==\nA conservation project (mainly supported by Zoo Basel) in Eritrea counted (before 2014) 47 Somali wild donkeys living in the mountains between the [[Buri Peninsula]] and the [[Dallol (volcano)|Dalool]] Depression, which is within the larger [[Danakil Depression]], near Eritrea's border with Ethiopia.<ref>{{cite web\n  |url=http://www.zoobasel.com/en/wissen/naturschutz/index.php?NSPID=6&apm=1_1&tpm=1_3\n  |title=Somali Wild Ass Research Project in Eritrea\n  |work=Conservation projects\n  |publisher=[[Zoo Basel]]\n  |accessdate=22 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n  |url=http://www.zoobasel.ch/en/wissen/naturschutz/index.php?NSPID=6&tp3=1_3\n  |title=Somali Wild Ass in Eritrea\n  |work=Conservation projects\n  |publisher=[[Zoo Basel]]\n  |accessdate=12 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n  |url=http://www.zoobasel.ch/cgi-bin/wissen/files/Report%20to%20Basel%20Zoo_for%20the%20website_2014.pdf\n  |title=Report to Basel Zoo - African wild ass (Equus africanus): Population dynamics, distribution and status in Eritrea\n  |date=August 2014\n  |author1=Moehlman, Patricia D. |author2=Yohannes, Hagos |author3=Teclai, Redae |author4=Hagos, Futsum\n |publisher=[[Zoo Basel]]\n  |accessdate=12 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n  |url=http://www.zoobasel.ch/cgi-bin/wissen/files/Report%20to%20Basel%20Zoo_for%20the%20website_2014.pdf\n  |title=Research and Community-Based Conservation of the African Wild Ass in the Danakil Desert of Ethiopia: Field Report\n  |date=July 2015\n  |author=Kebede, Fanuel\n  |publisher=[[Zoo Basel]]\n  |accessdate=12 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nAs mentioned above, a protected population of the Somali wild donkey exists in the [[Yotvata Hai-Bar Nature Reserve]]. This Israeli reserve was established in 1968 with the view to bolster populations of endangered desert species.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* Moehlman, Patricia D. (ed). 2002. [http://www.equids.org/docs/Moehlman_02_Low.pdf Equids: Zebras, Asses, and Horses: Status Survey and Conservation Action Plan]. [[Gland, Switzerland]]: IUCN/SCC Equid Specialist Group\n\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Equus africanus somaliensis}}\n* [https://www.stlzoo.org/animals/abouttheanimals/mammals/hoofedmammals/somaliwildass St. Louis Zoo: Somali Wild Ass]\n* [https://www.stlzoo.org/about/contact/pressroom/zoointhenews/somaliwildassproblem/ What's the Zoo to do with its wild ass problem?]  [[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]], accessed April 12, 2017\n* [http://awwp.alwabra.com/index.php/content/view/651/33/ Somali wild ass] at [[Al Wabra Wildlife Preserve]]\n\n{{Equus}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q603135}}\n\n[[Category:Equus]]\n[[Category:Herbivorous mammals]]\n