urrent distribution and habitat==\nThere are likely fewer than 1,000 animals (or even 700) in the wild<ref>{{cite web\n  |url=http://www.stlzoo.org/about/contact/pressroom/zoointhenews/somaliwildassproblem/\n  |author=Bonner, Jeffrey\n  |date=June 1, 2008\n  |title=What's the Zoo to do with its Somali wild ass problem?\n  |publisher=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]] & [[Saint Louis Zoo]]\n  |accessdate=12 April 2017}}</ref> and the ''[[International Union for Conservation of Nature|IUCN]] Red List of endangered species'' described it as \"critically endangered\". This means they face an extremely high risk of extinction in the wild.\n\nA few hundred specimens live in [[Somalia]], [[Eritrea]] and [[Ethiopia]].<ref name=\"Somali\">{{cite web\n  |url=http://www.zoobasel.ch/de/aktuell/detail.php?NEWSID=413&apm=1_4&nof\n  |title=Seltene Sch\u00f6nheit - Somali-Wildeselfohlen bezaubert das Zolli-Publikum\n  |date=16 December 2010\n  |publisher=[[Zoo Basel]]\n  |accessdate=12 April 2017\n  |language=de}}</ref>\n\n==Reproduction==\nSomali Wild Asses typically give birth in the spring, a common characteristic among equids, after a year-long gestation. Within hours, the foal is up on its legs and keeping up with its mother. At around five-days-old, the foal is already nibbling grass. By the time its two-weeks old, the foal is grazing regularly, however, still depending on its mother's milk for fluids. The foal is weaned by 12 to 14 months, but still stays close to its mother, only leaving to play or feed with the other foals in the herd.\n\n==Behavior==\nDue to the limited resources found in their habitat, Somali Wild Asses live in a fission-fusion society. Most adults live alone, but sometimes form small herds consisting of females and their young. In areas that have more resources, or have more rain, they will sometimes fuse together to form larger temporary herds.\nStallions can maintain territories as large as nine square miles. They frequently leave dung piles as markers to remind them of their territory's boundaries. While females are welcome in their territories, stallions will often fight other males who try to mate with females in their territories. However, stallions have been observed allowing males into their territories for grazing, as long as they show no interest in his harem. <ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://zoonooz.sandiegozoo.org/zoonooz/somali-wild-ass/|title=Somali Wild Ass|first=Wendy|last=Perkins|date=5 June 2017|website=ZOONOOZ}}</ref>\n\n==Captivity==\n\n===Global population===\n{{As of|2011}}, there are about 200 individuals in captivity around the globe<ref name=\"Somali\"/> living in 34 [[zoo]]s, as well as three animals (as of 2009) in the [[Yotvata Hai-Bar Nature Reserve]] in [[Israel]], to the north of [[Eilat]].<ref name=\"Stamm\">{{cite web| url=http://www.wst-foundation.ch/wcms/wsts.cfm/h,29/s,22/c,0/sc,de/blue.htm| title=Somali-Wildesel ''(Equus africanus somalicus)''| work=F\u00f6rderprojekte der Werner Stamm Stiftung| publisher=Werner Stamm Stiftung| accessdate=2011-11-14|language=de}}</ref>  The international [[studbook]] is managed by [[Tierpark Berlin]].<ref name=\"Direktoren\">{{cite web| url=http://www.zoodirektoren.de/index.php?option=com_k2&view=item&id=179:somali-wildesel-equus-africanus-somalicus&Itemid=255| title=Somali-Wildesel| publisher=[[Verband Deutscher Zoodirektoren]]| accessdate=22 May 2014|language=de}}</ref>\n\n===Zoo Basel===\n[[File:ZolliWildAss.JPG|thumb|Somali Wild Ass at [[Zoo Basel]]]]\nThe leading zoo for breeding this rare ass is [[Zoo Basel]], Switzerland. Its [[Breeding programs at Zoo Basel|breeding program]] manages the [[Europe]]an studbook for the Somali wild ass and coordinates the [[European Endangered Species Programme]] (EEP)<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.zoobasel.ch/aktuell/detail.php?NEWSID=187&PHPSESSID=34277fba68d5857ecdb43ae645c9831c%7CZoo | title=INDIAN RHINO VISION (IRV) 2020| date=8 May 2008| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120315234046/http://www.zoobasel.ch/aktuell/detail.php?NEWSID=187&PHPSESSID=34277fba68d5857ecdb43ae645c9831c%7CZoo| archivedate=15 March 2012| publisher=[[Zoo Basel]]| accessdate=22 May 2014|language=de}}</ref> \u2013 as well as the global species committee of the Somali Wild Ass since 2004.<ref name=\"Stamm\" />\n\nZoo Basel started keeping Somali wild asses in 1970 and had its first birth in 1972.  Since then, 11 stallions and 24 females (as of 2009) were born and survived childhood.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.zoobasel.ch/de/aktuell/detail.php?NEWSID=140&apm=1_4&nof| title=Zweites Somali-Wildeselfohlen im Zolli geboren | date=27 December 2007| publisher=[[Zoo Basel]]| accessdate=22 May 2014|language=de}}</ref> Today, all Somali wild donkeys in captivity are related to the original group at Zoo Basel.<ref name=\"Direktoren\"/>\n\nAs of January 18, 2012, there are four Somali wild donkeys in Basel: The stallion \"Gigolo\" (3) and three females (among them \"Yogala\"-14).<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.zoobasel.com/en/aktuell/detail.php?NEWSID=499&apm=1_4&nof| title=Dance of the Somali wild asses| date=18 January 2012| publisher=[[Zoo Basel]]|accessdate=22 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n===France===\nSince 1987, the [[R\u00e9serve Africaine de Sigean]], in the south of [[France]], has had a number of Somali wild asses, with births occurring regularly, including two on June 30, 2010 and March 29, 2013.<ref>{{cite web\n  |url=http://archives-lepost.huffingtonpost.fr/article/2010/07/07/2143765_naissance-rare-au-zoo-de-sigean-un-ane-de-somalie.html\n  |title=Naissance rare au zoo de Sigean: un \u00e2ne de Somalie!\n  |publisher=[[Le Huffington Post]] (French-language edition of the [[Huffington Post]])\n  |date=July 7, 2010\n  |language=fr\n  |accessdate= 12 April 2017\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n  |url=http://www.ladepeche.fr/article/2013/04/27/1615575-une-naissance-tres-rare-a-la-reserve-de-sigean.html\n  |title=Une naissance tr\u00e8s rare \u00e0 la R\u00e9serve de Sigean\n  |publisher=[[La D\u00e9p\u00eache du Midi]]\n  |date=April 27, 2013\n  |language=fr\n  |accessdate= 12 April 2017\n}}</ref>\n\n===United States===\nOnly four institutions breed Somali wild ass in the [[United States]]:<ref name=\"whiteoak\">{{cite web| url=http://www.whiteoakwildlife.org/animal-programs/somali-wild-ass/| title=Somali Wild Ass| work=Animal Programs| publisher=[[White Oak Conservation|White Oak]]| accessdate=22 May 2014 }}</ref> [[Dallas Zoo]], [[St. Louis Zoo]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Somali wild ass born at St. Louis Zoo|url=http://www.connecttristates.com/news/story.aspx?id=125173#.UcSpdo4rV8s|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|accessdate=21 June 2013}}</ref> [[San Diego Zoo Safari Park]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Three Somali Wild Ass Foals Born At San Diego Zoo Safari Park|url=http://media.sandiegozoo.org/2011/07/13/three-somali-wild-ass-foals-born-at-san-diego-zoo-safari-park/|publisher=San Diego Zoo|accessdate=21 June 2013}}</ref> and [[White Oak Conservation]] in [[Yulee, Florida]].<ref name=\"whiteoak\"/> White Oak received a herd in 2008 as part of an international effort to save Somali wild ass from extinction. Since then, the herd has produced 18 [[foals]], including several born in spring 2013.<ref name=\"whiteoak\"/> The Dallas Zoo has just had two Somali wild ass foals, both female, one born July 9 and the other on July 19, 2017.  The St. Louis Zoo's most recent birth was on July 30, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stlzoo.org/about/contact/pressroom/pressreleases/somali-wild-ass-foal-born-july-30-2019|title=Somali wild ass foal born July 30, 2019|date=27 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe San Diego Zoo Safari Park is home to eleven Somali Wild Asses, the largest population of Somali Wild Asses in North America. The park received its first herd from the Basel Zoo in 1981. Their first foal was born in 1986. Since then, 49 foals have been born, the most recent being a female born on March 17, 2018. San Diego Zoo Global also works to help save this endangered species in the wild. <ref name=\"auto\"/> <ref>{{cite web|url=http://zoonooz.sandiegozoo.org/2018/04/12/somali-wild-ass-foal-explores-habitat/|title=Somali Wild Ass Foal Explores Habitat|first=Public|last=Relations|date=12 April 2018|website=ZOONOOZ}}</ref>\n\n===Domestication===\n[[File:Somali wild ass pair.jpg|thumb|right|Two Somali Wild Ass at [[Marwell Wildlife|Marwell Zoo]]]]\nDomestic [[donkey]]s found in [[Italy]] are typically descended from the Somali wild ass, as opposed to those from other European countries where domesticated stock are usually descended from the [[Nubian wild ass]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/cambridgeshire/hi/people_and_places/history/newsid_9150000/9150180.stm|title=Pompeii Horse Is in Fact an Ass|date=3 November 2010|publisher = [[BBC]]}}</ref>{{Citation needed|date=September 2014|reason=This statement is not exactly what the source says: \"Italian donkeys are typically descended from the Somali wild ass\" is not exactly the same as what the source says, which is that those donkeys which are derived from the Somali wild ass are typically found in Italy (the former implies all Italian donkeys, but the latter may be talking about only a few of the Italian donkeys).  But in any case, we need a direct ref for this, not just a local BBC report which does not give its own refs.}}\n\n==Conservation==\nA conservation project (mainly supported by Zoo Basel) in Eritrea counted (before 2014) 47 Somali wild asses living in the mountains between the [[Buri Peninsula]] and the [[Dallol (volcano)|Dalool]] Depression, which is within the larger [[Danakil Depression]], near Eritrea's border with Ethiopia.<ref>{{cite web\n  |url=http://www.zoobasel.com/en/wissen/naturschutz/index.php?NSPID=6&apm=1_1&tpm=1_3\n  |title=Somali Wild Ass Research Project in Eritrea\n  |work=Conservation projects\n  |publisher=[[Zoo Basel]]\n  |accessdate=22 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n  |url=http://www.zoobasel.ch/en/wissen/naturschutz/index.php?NSPID=6&tp3=1_3\n  |title=Somali Wild Ass in Eritrea\n  |work=Conservation projects\n  |publisher=[[Zoo Basel]]\n  |accessdate=12 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n  |url=http://www.zoobasel.ch/cgi-bin/wissen/files/Report%20to%20Basel%20Zoo_for%20the%20website_2014.pdf\n  |title=Report to Basel Zoo - African wild ass (Equus africanus): Population dynamics, distribution and status in Eritrea\n  |date=August 2014\n  |author1=Moehlman, Patricia D. |author2=Yohannes, Hagos |author3=Teclai, Redae |author4=Hagos, Futsum\n |publisher=[[Zoo Basel]]\n  |accessdate=12 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n  |url=http://www.zoobasel.ch/cgi-bin/wissen/files/Report%20to%20Basel%20Zoo_for%20the%20website_2014.pdf\n  |title=Research and Community-Based Conservation of the African Wild Ass in the Danakil Desert of Ethiopia: Field Report\n  |date=July 2015\n  |author=Kebede, Fanuel\n  |publisher=[[Zoo Basel]]\n  |accessdate=12 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nAs mentioned above, a protected population of the Somali wild ass exists in the [[Yotvata Hai-Bar Nature Reserve]]. This Israeli reserve was established in 1968 with the view to bolster populations of endangered desert species.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* Moehlman, Patricia D. (ed). 2002. [http://www.equids.org/docs/Moehlman_02_Low.pdf Equids: Zebras, Asses, and Horses: Status Survey and Conservation Action Plan]. [[Gland, Switzerland]]: IUCN/SCC Equid Specialist Group\n\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Equus africanus somaliensis}}\n* [https://www.stlzoo.org/animals/abouttheanimals/mammals/hoofedmammals/somaliwildass St. Louis Zoo: Somali Wild Ass]\n* [https://www.stlzoo.org/about/contact/pressroom/zoointhenews/somaliwildassproblem/ What's the Zoo to do with its wild ass problem?]  [[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]], accessed April 12, 2017\n* [http://awwp.alwabra.com/index.php/content/view/651/33/ Somali wild ass] at [[Al Wabra Wildlife Preserve]]\n\n{{Equus}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q603135}}\n\n[[Category:Equus]]\n[[Category:Herbivorous mammals]]\n[[Category:Mammals described in 1884]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Eritrea]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Somalia]]\n", "name_user": "Electos242", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Somali_wild_donkey"}
{"title_page": "Roland Orzabal", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name             = Roland Orzabal\n| image            = File:R orzabal.jpg\n| caption          = Orzabal in 2007\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Roland Jaime Orzabal de la Quintana\n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1961|08|22}}\n| birth_place      = [[Portsmouth]], Hampshire, England\n| death_date       = \n| origin           = [[Bath, Somerset]], England\n| instrument       = {{hlist|Vocals|guitars|keyboards}}\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[New wave music|New wave]]|[[pop rock]]|[[synth-pop]]}}\n| occupation       = {{hlist|Musician|singer|songwriter|record producer|author}}\n| years_active     = \n| label            = {{hlist|[[Mercury Records|Mercury]]|[[Eagle Records|Eagle]]|[[Epic Records|Epic]]}}\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[Tears for Fears]]|[[Graduate (band)|Graduate]]|[[Neon (British band)|Neon]]|Mancrab|[[Oleta Adams]]|[[Emil\u00edana Torrini]]}}\n| website          = \n}}\n\n'''Roland Orzabal''' (born 22 August 1961) is an English musician, singer-songwriter, and record producer. He is best known as a co-founder of [[Tears for Fears]], of which he is the main songwriter, guitarist, occasional keyboardist and joint vocalist, but he has also achieved success as a producer of other artists including [[Oleta Adams]] and [[Emiliana Torrini]]. In 2014, Orzabal published his first novel. \n\nOrzabal is noted for his idiosyncratic approach to songwriting, melodic guitar playing and distinctive wide ranging voice. he also plays keyboards on studio recordings.\n\nOrzabal, with [[Curt Smith]] are responsible for discovering musician and songwriter [[Oleta Adams]], whom they brought into the band and who sang on the single [[Woman in Chains]] from the 1989 Tears for Fears album ''[[The Seeds of Love]]'' as a duet with Orzabal.<ref name=\"vh1\">[http://www.vh1.com/artists/az/adams_oleta/bio.jhtml VH1.com] Biography Oleta Adams. (Retrieved: September 15, 2006)</ref>  Orzabal co-produced [[Oleta Adams]]' album ''[[Circle of One]]'' (1990). The album reached No. 1 in the UK and No. 20 in the US, and featured her transatlantic top ten hit \"[[Get Here]]\". Orzabal also co-wrote the lead track \"Rhythm of Life\" for the album, which was originally intended for ''[[The Seeds of Love]]''. As well as playing guitar and singing backing vocals on the track, he also appeared in the song's accompanying promo video.\n\n\n==Early life==\nOrzabal was born in [[Portsmouth]], [[Hampshire]].<ref name=\"tears\"/> Initially raised in [[Havant]],{{cn|reason=Neither Havant nor Leigh Park in cited source, most Parkies were born at M.U. on Portsea and as Leigh Park part of Havant Borough have left as Havant|date=June 2019}} his family later moved to [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]] where he attended [[Culverhay School]] and became a member of the [[Zenith Youth Theatre Company]].<ref name=tears>{{cite web|title=All about Roland Orzabal|url=http://www.tearsforfears.net/all-about-roland-orzabal/|publisher=Tears for fears|accessdate=10 February 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118061246/http://www.tearsforfears.net/all-about-roland-orzabal/|archive-date=18 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nOrzabal's mother is English and his father (George Orzabal de la Quintana) is from Paris, France, of Spanish-[[Basque people|Basque]] descent.<ref name=tears/> Roland's grandfather, Arturo Orzabal de la Quintana, was from [[Buenos Aires]], Argentina, and son of emigrants from the [[Basque Country (greater region)|Basque Country]]. Orzabal was named Raoul for the first two weeks after his birth, but this was changed to Roland to [[Anglicisation|anglicise]] the name as the family was living in England. When Orzabal was three years old, his father had a [[nervous breakdown]] which left him semi-bedridden for a large portion of Orzabal's childhood. His father decided to run an entertainment business with his mother, a dancer, resulting in different entertainers often hanging around Orzabal's home. He describes his childhood as \"unorthodox,\" and it inspired various Tears for Fears songs, particularly on ''[[The Hurting]]''.\n\n==Career==\n===Early career===\n{{main|Tears for Fears}}\nOrzabal met [[Curt Smith]] while both were in their early teens in [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]], Somerset.  In the late-1970s, they formed a [[Mod (subculture)|mod]] music group, [[Graduate (band)|Graduate]], along with three other members. Following the release of their debut album, ''Acting My Age'', the group disbanded and Orzabal and Smith went on to form [[Tears for Fears]], a [[New wave music|new wave]]/[[synthpop]] outfit directly inspired by the writings of the American psychologist [[Arthur Janov]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Biography of Tears for Fears|url=http://www.poemhunter.com/lyrics/tears-for-fears/biography/|publisher=Poem Hunter|accessdate=10 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Solo work===\nAfter a decade of major international success, Orzabal and Smith acrimoniously split in the early 1990s. Orzabal continued to work as Tears for Fears after he and Smith parted ways; the subsequent albums ''[[Elemental (Tears for Fears album)|Elemental]]''&nbsp;(1993) and ''[[Raoul and the Kings of Spain]]''&nbsp;(1995) are effectively solo works by him in all but name. ''Elemental'' was a success being certified as Gold status in the US and Silver in the UK, while ''Raoul'' took a more artistic direction but garnered less chart success. In 2001 he released his first proper solo album, ''[[Tomcats Screaming Outside]]'', under his own name.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tomcats Screaming Outside: AllMusic Review |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/tomcats-screaming-outside-mw0000012043 |publisher=AllMusic |accessdate=10 February 2013 |first=MacKenzie |last=Wilson |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190503065036/https://www.allmusic.com/album/tomcats-screaming-outside-mw0000012043 |archive-date=3 May 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Orzabal and Smith had reconciled by that point and were working together on Tears for Fears's next album, ''[[Everybody Loves a Happy Ending]]''&nbsp;(2004).\n\n===Work as a producer/songwriter===\nAs a songwriter, Orzabal is a two-time [[Ivor Novello Award]] winner. His first award was in 1986 for \"Songwriter of the Year\" following the release of Tears for Fears' second album ''[[Songs from the Big Chair]]'' for which Orzabal wrote or co-wrote all of the tracks.<ref>{{cite web|title=Songs From The Big Chair|url=http://aln2.albumlinernotes.com/Songs_From_The_Big_Chair.html|publisher=Album Liner Notes|accessdate=10 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nOrzabal, with [[Curt Smith]] are responsible for discovering musician and songwriter [[Oleta Adams]], whom they brought into the band and who sang on the single [[Woman in Chains]] from the 1989 Tears for Fears album ''[[The Seeds of Love]]'' as a duet with Orzabal.<ref name=\"vh1\">[http://www.vh1.com/artists/az/adams_oleta/bio.jhtml VH1.com] Biography Oleta Adams. (Retrieved: September 15, 2006)</ref>  Orzabal co-produced [[Oleta Adams]]' album ''[[Circle of One]]'' (1990). The album reached No. 1 in the UK and No. 20 in the US, and featured her transatlantic top ten hit \"[[Get Here]]\". Orzabal also co-wrote the lead track \"Rhythm of Life\" for the album, which was originally intended for ''[[The Seeds of Love]]''. As well as playing guitar and singing backing vocals on the track, he also appeared in the song's accompanying promo video.\n\nIn 1999, Orzabal co-produced the Icelandic singer-songwriter [[Emiliana Torrini]]'s album ''[[Love in the Time of Science]]'', along with Tears for Fears associate [[Apartment (Bristol band)|Alan Griffiths]]. The pair also wrote two tracks for the album.<ref>{{cite web|title=Love in the Time of Science|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/love-in-the-time-of-science-mw0000616241|publisher=allmusic|accessdate=10 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nOrzabal's talents as a songwriter were recognised again after [[Michael Andrews (musician)|Michael Andrews]] and [[Gary Jules]] recorded the song \"[[Mad World]]\" for the film soundtrack ''[[Donnie Darko]]'' in 2001.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mad World (Alternate Version) Lyrics|url=http://www.stlyrics.com/songs/r/rolandorzabal23371/madworldalternateversion2075437.html|publisher=ST Lyrics|accessdate=10 February 2013}}</ref> Their version was released as a single in 2003 and became the Christmas number one single in the UK that year, ultimately becoming the year's biggest selling single. The song was originally composed by Orzabal and was Tears for Fears' first hit single in 1982. In 2004, the song won Orzabal his second [[Ivor Novello Award]], as the songwriter of the Best Selling UK Single of 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/the_darkness_scoop_ivor_novello_award_1_64997|title=Ivor Novello Awards 2004 (East Anglian Daily Times 24)|work=East Anglian Daily Times|accessdate=28 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Other activities==\n===Novel===\nOrzabal has written a novel, a romantic comedy entitled ''Sex, Drugs & Opera'', published in 2014. It tells the story of a middle-aged pop star, Solomon Capri, who is semi-retired but is approached to take part in the reality show ''[[Popstar to Operastar]]'' which he sees as a way to rejuvenate his career and his waning marriage. The story was inspired by Orzabal's own experience as he was approached by the ITV show himself, though did not take part.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tears For Fears' Roland Orzabal Turns Author with the Release of Sex, Drugs & Opera|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/press/tears-for-fears-roland-orzabal-turns-author-with-the-release-of-sex-drugs|publisher=Contact Music|accessdate=8 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Orzabal|first=Roland|title=Sex, Drugs & Opera: There's Life After Rock 'n' Roll|date=2014|publisher=Crucial 7th Publishing|location=London|isbn=978-1909122710}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1985, Orzabal gained considerable press attention for his strained relationship with his father and a humorous cartoon was printed in the UK tabloid ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' pertaining to this. The cartoon was later reprinted within the cover artwork for the Tears for Fears single \"[[I Believe (Tears for Fears song)|I Believe]]\".<ref name=tears/>\n\nOrzabal married Caroline (n\u00e9e Johnston) at Bath Register Office in 1982.<ref>{{cite web|title=Roland Orzabal|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1090844/bio|publisher=Internet Movie Database|accessdate=10 February 2013}}</ref> The couple have two sons, born in 1991 and 1994. Caroline can be heard singing the child vocal on the Tears for Fears song \"[[Suffer the Children (song)|Suffer the Children]]\" from the band's debut album ''The Hurting'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Tears for Fears \" The Hurting\"|url=http://coolalbumreview.com/?p=12045|publisher=Cool album review|accessdate=10 February 2013}}</ref> and also drew the \"hands\" cover artwork for the 1983 re-release of \"[[Pale Shelter]]\".\n\nIn July 2017, Caroline died from natural causes and [[Tears for Fears]] initially withdrew from the remaining shows on the North American tour they were co-headlining with [[Hall & Oates]], citing a family emergency. Roland and Tears for Fears resumed the tour on 14 September 2017, at the [[Staples Center]] in Los Angeles.<ref name=\"Resched\">{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180529170038/https://www.staplescenter.com/assets/doc/Hall-Oates_Tears-For-Fears_RESCHEDULED-DATES_FINAL-824ac08c95.pdf|website=Staples Center|title=Daryl Hall & John Oates and Tears for Fears reschedule the Los Angeles and San Jose Shows|access-date=29 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180529170038/https://www.staplescenter.com/assets/doc/Hall-Oates_Tears-For-Fears_RESCHEDULED-DATES_FINAL-824ac08c95.pdf|archive-date=29 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===Solo albums===\n*''[[Tomcats Screaming Outside]]'' (2001)\n\n===with Graduate===\n*''Acting My Age'' (1980)\n\n===with Tears for Fears===\n*''[[The Hurting]]'' (1983)\n*''[[Songs from the Big Chair]]'' (1985)\n*''[[The Seeds of Love]]'' (1989)\n*''[[Elemental (Tears for Fears album)|Elemental]]'' (1993)\n*''[[Raoul and the Kings of Spain]]'' (1995)\n*''[[Everybody Loves a Happy Ending]]'' (2004)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n\n{{Commonscat}}\n\n{{Tears for Fears}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Orzabal, Roland}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century English singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century English singers]]\n[[Category:APRA Award winners]]\n[[Category:British people of Basque descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Spanish descent]]\n[[Category:English male singers]]\n[[Category:English new wave musicians]]\n[[Category:English songwriters]]\n[[Category:English record producers]]\n[[Category:Male new wave singers]]\n[[Category:English rock singers]]\n[[Category:English socialists]]\n[[Category:Tears for Fears members]]\n[[Category:People from Portsmouth]]\n[[Category:Ivor Novello Award winners]]\n\n[[Category:People from Havant]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name             = Roland Orzabal\n| image            = File:R orzabal.jpg\n| caption          = Orzabal in 2007\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Roland Jaime Orzabal de la Quintana\n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1961|08|22}}\n| birth_place      = [[Portsmouth]], Hampshire, England\n| death_date       = \n| origin           = [[Bath, Somerset]], England\n| instrument       = {{hlist|Vocals|guitars|keyboards}}\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[New wave music|New wave]]|[[pop rock]]|[[synth-pop]]}}\n| occupation       = {{hlist|Musician|singer|songwriter|record producer|author}}\n| years_active     = \n| label            = {{hlist|[[Mercury Records|Mercury]]|[[Eagle Records|Eagle]]|[[Epic Records|Epic]]}}\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[Tears for Fears]]|[[Graduate (band)|Graduate]]|[[Neon (British band)|Neon]]|Mancrab|[[Oleta Adams]]|[[Emil\u00edana Torrini]]}}\n| website          = \n}}\n\n'''Roland Orzabal''' (born 22 August 1961) is an English musician, singer-songwriter, and record producer. He is best known as a co-founder of [[Tears for Fears]], of which he is the main songwriter, guitarist and joint vocalist, but he has also achieved success as a producer of other artists including [[Oleta Adams]] and [[Emiliana Torrini]]. In 2014, Orzabal published his first novel. \n\nOrzabal, with [[Curt Smith]] are responsible for discovering musician and songwriter [[Oleta Adams]], whom they brought into the band and who sang on the single [[Woman in Chains]] from the 1989 Tears for Fears album ''[[The Seeds of Love]]'' as a duet with Orzabal.<ref name=\"vh1\">[http://www.vh1.com/artists/az/adams_oleta/bio.jhtml VH1.com] Biography Oleta Adams. (Retrieved: September 15, 2006)</ref>  Orzabal co-produced [[Oleta Adams]]' album ''[[Circle of One]]'' (1990). The album reached No. 1 in the UK and No. 20 in the US, and featured her transatlantic top ten hit \"[[Get Here]]\". Orzabal also co-wrote the lead track \"Rhythm of Life\" for the album, which was originally intended for ''[[The Seeds of Love]]''. As well as playing guitar and singing backing vocals on the track, he also appeared in the song's accompanying promo video.\n\n\n==Early life==\nOrzabal was born in [[Portsmouth]], [[Hampshire]].<ref name=\"tears\"/> Initially raised in [[Havant]],{{cn|reason=Neither Havant nor Leigh Park in cited source, most Parkies were born at M.U. on Portsea and as Leigh Park part of Havant Borough have left as Havant|date=June 2019}} his family later moved to [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]] where he attended [[Culverhay School]] and became a member of the [[Zenith Youth Theatre Company]].<ref name=tears>{{cite web|title=All about Roland Orzabal|url=http://www.tearsforfears.net/all-about-roland-orzabal/|publisher=Tears for fears|accessdate=10 February 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118061246/http://www.tearsforfears.net/all-about-roland-orzabal/|archive-date=18 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nOrzabal's mother is English and his father (George Orzabal de la Quintana) is from Paris, France, of Spanish-[[Basque people|Basque]] descent.<ref name=tears/> Roland's grandfather, Arturo Orzabal de la Quintana, was from [[Buenos Aires]], Argentina, and son of emigrants from the [[Basque Country (greater region)|Basque Country]]. Orzabal was named Raoul for the first two weeks after his birth, but this was changed to Roland to [[Anglicisation|anglicise]] the name as the family was living in England. When Orzabal was three years old, his father had a [[nervous breakdown]] which left him semi-bedridden for a large portion of Orzabal's childhood. His father decided to run an entertainment business with his mother, a dancer, resulting in different entertainers often hanging around Orzabal's home. He describes his childhood as \"unorthodox,\" and it inspired various Tears for Fears songs, particularly on ''[[The Hurting]]''.\n\n==Career==\n===Early career===\n{{main|Tears for Fears}}\nOrzabal met [[Curt Smith]] while both were in their early teens in [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]], Somerset.  In the late-1970s, they formed a [[Mod (subculture)|mod]] music group, [[Graduate (band)|Graduate]], along with three other members. Following the release of their debut album, ''Acting My Age'', the group disbanded and Orzabal and Smith went on to form [[Tears for Fears]], a [[New wave music|new wave]]/[[synthpop]] outfit directly inspired by the writings of the American psychologist [[Arthur Janov]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Biography of Tears for Fears|url=http://www.poemhunter.com/lyrics/tears-for-fears/biography/|publisher=Poem Hunter|accessdate=10 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Solo work===\nAfter a decade of major international success, Orzabal and Smith acrimoniously split in the early 1990s. Orzabal continued to work as Tears for Fears after he and Smith parted ways; the subsequent albums ''[[Elemental (Tears for Fears album)|Elemental]]''&nbsp;(1993) and ''[[Raoul and the Kings of Spain]]''&nbsp;(1995) are effectively solo works by him in all but name. ''Elemental'' was a success being certified as Gold status in the US and Silver in the UK, while ''Raoul'' took a more artistic direction but garnered less chart success. In 2001 he released his first proper solo album, ''[[Tomcats Screaming Outside]]'', under his own name.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tomcats Screaming Outside: AllMusic Review |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/tomcats-screaming-outside-mw0000012043 |publisher=AllMusic |accessdate=10 February 2013 |first=MacKenzie |last=Wilson |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190503065036/https://www.allmusic.com/album/tomcats-screaming-outside-mw0000012043 |archive-date=3 May 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Orzabal and Smith had reconciled by that point and were working together on Tears for Fears's next album, ''[[Everybody Loves a Happy Ending]]''&nbsp;(2004).\n\n===Work as a producer/songwriter===\nAs a songwriter, Orzabal is a two-time [[Ivor Novello Award]] winner. His first award was in 1986 for \"Songwriter of the Year\" following the release of Tears for Fears' second album ''[[Songs from the Big Chair]]'' for which Orzabal wrote or co-wrote all of the tracks.<ref>{{cite web|title=Songs From The Big Chair|url=http://aln2.albumlinernotes.com/Songs_From_The_Big_Chair.html|publisher=Album Liner Notes|accessdate=10 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nOrzabal, with [[Curt Smith]] are responsible for discovering musician and songwriter [[Oleta Adams]], whom they brought into the band and who sang on the single [[Woman in Chains]] from the 1989 Tears for Fears album ''[[The Seeds of Love]]'' as a duet with Orzabal.<ref name=\"vh1\">[http://www.vh1.com/artists/az/adams_oleta/bio.jhtml VH1.com] Biography Oleta Adams. (Retrieved: September 15, 2006)</ref>  Orzabal co-produced [[Oleta Adams]]' album ''[[Circle of One]]'' (1990). The album reached No. 1 in the UK and No. 20 in the US, and featured her transatlantic top ten hit \"[[Get Here]]\". Orzabal also co-wrote the lead track \"Rhythm of Life\" for the album, which was originally intended for ''[[The Seeds of Love]]''. As well as playing guitar and singing backing vocals on the track, he also appeared in the song's accompanying promo video.\n\nIn 1999, Orzabal co-produced the Icelandic singer-songwriter [[Emiliana Torrini]]'s album ''[[Love in the Time of Science]]'', along with Tears for Fears associate [[Apartment (Bristol band)|Alan Griffiths]]. The pair also wrote two tracks for the album.<ref>{{cite web|title=Love in the Time of Science|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/love-in-the-time-of-science-mw0000616241|publisher=allmusic|accessdate=10 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nOrzabal's talents as a songwriter were recognised again after [[Michael Andrews (musician)|Michael Andrews]] and [[Gary Jules]] recorded the song \"[[Mad World]]\" for the film soundtrack ''[[Donnie Darko]]'' in 2001.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mad World (Alternate Version) Lyrics|url=http://www.stlyrics.com/songs/r/rolandorzabal23371/madworldalternateversion2075437.html|publisher=ST Lyrics|accessdate=10 February 2013}}</ref> Their version was released as a single in 2003 and became the Christmas number one single in the UK that year, ultimately becoming the year's biggest selling single. The song was originally composed by Orzabal and was Tears for Fears' first hit single in 1982. In 2004, the song won Orzabal his second [[Ivor Novello Award]], as the songwriter of the Best Selling UK Single of 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eadt.co.uk/news/the_darkness_scoop_ivor_novello_award_1_64997|title=Ivor Novello Awards 2004 (East Anglian Daily Times 24)|work=East Anglian Daily Times|accessdate=28 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Other activities==\n===Novel===\nOrzabal has written a novel, a romantic comedy entitled ''Sex, Drugs & Opera'', published in 2014. It tells the story of a middle-aged pop star, Solomon Capri, who is semi-retired but is approached to take part in the reality show ''[[Popstar to Operastar]]'' which he sees as a way to rejuvenate his career and his waning marriage. The story was inspired by Orzabal's own experience as he was approached by the ITV show himself, though did not take part.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tears For Fears' Roland Orzabal Turns Author with the Release of Sex, Drugs & Opera|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/press/tears-for-fears-roland-orzabal-turns-author-with-the-release-of-sex-drugs|publisher=Contact Music|accessdate=8 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Orzabal|first=Roland|title=Sex, Drugs & Opera: There's Life After Rock 'n' Roll|date=2014|publisher=Crucial 7th Publishing|location=London|isbn=978-1909122710}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1985, Orzabal gained considerable press attention for his strained relationship with his father and a humorous cartoon was printed in the UK tabloid ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' pertaining to this. The cartoon was later reprinted within the cover artwork for the Tears for Fears single \"[[I Believe (Tears for Fears song)|I Believe]]\".<ref name=tears/>\n\nOrzabal married Caroline (n\u00e9e Johnston) at Bath Register Office in 1982.<ref>{{cite web|title=Roland Orzabal|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1090844/bio|publisher=Internet Movie Database|accessdate=10 February 2013}}</ref> The couple have two sons, born in 1991 and 1994. Caroline can be heard singing the child vocal on the Tears for Fears song \"[[Suffer the Children (song)|Suffer the Children]]\" from the band's debut album ''The Hurting'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Tears for Fears \" The Hurting\"|url=http://coolalbumreview.com/?p=12045|publisher=Cool album review|accessdate=10 February 2013}}</ref> and also drew the \"hands\" cover artwork for the 1983 re-release of \"[[Pale Shelter]]\".\n\nIn July 2017, Caroline died from natural causes and [[Tears for Fears]] initially withdrew from the remaining shows on the North American tour they were co-headlining with [[Hall & Oates]], citing a family emergency. Roland and Tears for Fears resumed the tour on 14 September 2017, at the [[Staples Center]] in Los Angeles.<ref name=\"Resched\">{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180529170038/https://www.staplescenter.com/assets/doc/Hall-Oates_Tears-For-Fears_RESCHEDULED-DATES_FINAL-824ac08c95.pdf|website=Staples Center|title=Daryl Hall & John Oates and Tears for Fears reschedule the Los Angeles and San Jose Shows|access-date=29 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180529170038/https://www.staplescenter.com/assets/doc/Hall-Oates_Tears-For-Fears_RESCHEDULED-DATES_FINAL-824ac08c95.pdf|archive-date=29 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===Solo albums===\n*''[[Tomcats Screaming Outside]]'' (2001)\n\n===with Graduate===\n*''Acting My Age'' (1980)\n\n===with Tears for Fears===\n*''[[The Hurting]]'' (1983)\n*''[[Songs from the Big Chair]]'' (1985)\n*''[[The Seeds of Love]]'' (1989)\n*''[[Elemental (Tears for Fears album)|Elemental]]'' (1993)\n*''[[Raoul and the Kings of Spain]]'' (1995)\n*''[[Everybody Loves a Happy Ending]]'' (2004)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n\n{{Commonscat}}\n\n{{Tears for Fears}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Orzabal, Roland}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century English singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century English singers]]\n[[Category:APRA Award winners]]\n[[Category:British people of Basque descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Spanish descent]]\n[[Category:English male singers]]\n[[Category:English new wave musicians]]\n[[Category:English songwriters]]\n[[Category:English record producers]]\n[[Category:Male new wave singers]]\n[[Category:English rock singers]]\n[[Category:English socialists]]\n[[Category:Tears for Fears members]]\n[[Category:People from Portsmouth]]\n[[Category:Ivor Novello Award winners]]\n\n[[Category:People from Havant]]\n", "name_user": "Tobystewart", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roland_Orzabal"}
{"title_page": "Miroslav Holub", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Miloslav Holub}}\n{{More footnotes|date=September 2010}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name             = Miroslav Holub\n| embed            = \n| honorific_prefix = [[MUDr.]]\n| honorific_suffix = [[DrSc.]]\n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| image_upright    = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| pseudonym        = \n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       =  {{Birth date  |df=yes|1923|9|13}}  \n| birth_place      = [[ Plze\u0148]], [[Czechoslovakia]]\n| death_date       =   {{Death date and age|df=yes|1998|7|14|1923|9|13}} \n| death_place      = [[Prague]], [[Czech Republic]]\n| resting_place    = \n| occupation       = poet, immunologist\n| language         = [[Czech language|Czech]]\n| nationality      =  [[Czech people|Czech]]\n| citizenship      = \n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = [[Czechoslovak Academy of Sciences]]\n| period           = \n| genre            = <!-- or: | genres = -->\n| subject          = <!-- or: | subjects = -->\n| movement         = \n| notableworks     = <!-- or: | notablework = -->\n| spouse           = <!-- or: | spouses = -->\n| partner          = <!-- or: | partners = -->\n| children         = \n| relatives        = \n| awards           = \n| signature        = \n| signature_alt    = \n| years_active     = 1958\u201396\n| module           = \n| website          = <!-- {{URL|example.org}} -->\n| portaldisp       = <!-- \"on\", \"yes\", \"true\", etc; or omit -->\n}}\n'''Miroslav Holub''' ({{IPA-cs|m\u026ar\u0254slaf \u0266\u0254l\u028ap|pron}}; 13 September 1923 \u2013 14 July 1998) was a [[Czech Republic|Czech]] [[poet]] and [[Immunology|immunologist]].\n\nHolub's work was heavily influenced by his experiences as an [[Immunologist]], writing many poems using his scientific knowledge to poetic effect. His work is almost always un[[rhyme]]d, so lends itself easily to [[translation]]. It has been translated into more than 30 languages and is especially popular in the [[English language|English]]-speaking world. Although one of the most internationally well-known Czech poets, his reputation continues to languish at home.\n\nHolub was born in [[Plze\u0148]].  His first book in Czech was ''Denn\u00ed slu\u017eba'' (1958), which abandoned the somewhat Stalinist bent of poems earlier in the decade (published in magazines).\n\nIn English, he was first published in the ''[[The Observer|Observer]]'' in 1962, and five years later a ''Selected Poems'' appeared in the Penguin Modern European Poets imprint, with an introduction by [[Al Alvarez]] and translations by [[Ian Milner]] and George Theiner. Holub's work was lauded by many, including [[Ted Hughes]] and [[Seamus Heaney]],<ref>The New York Times, 22 July 1998</ref> and his influence is visible in Hughes' collection ''[[Crow (poetry)|Crow]]'' (1970).\n\nIn addition to poetry, Holub wrote many short essays on various aspects of science, particularly biology and medicine (specifically immunology) and life. A collection of these, titled ''The Dimension of the Present Moment,'' is still in print. In the 1960s, he published two books of what he called 'semi-reportage' about extended visits to the United States.\n\nThe [[minor planet]] [[List_of_minor_planets:_7001\u20138000#401|7496 Miroslavholub]], an [[outer main belt asteroid]], is named in his honour.\n\n==Works in translation==\n* ''Vanishing Lung Syndrome,'' trans. David Young and Dana Habova (Oberlin College Press, 1990). {{ISBN|0-932440-52-5}}; (Faber and Faber, 1990). {{ISBN|0-571-14339-3}}\n* ''Intensive Care: Selected and New Poems,'' ed. David Young (Oberlin College Press, 1996). {{ISBN|0-932440-76-2}}\n* ''The Rampage,'' trans. David Young, Dana H\u00e1bov\u00e1, Rebekah Bloyd and the author (Faber and Faber 1997) {{ISBN|0-571-19253-X}}\n* ''Poems Before and After: Collected English Translations'' (Bloodaxe Books; 2nd ed. 2006). {{ISBN|1-85224-747-9}}\n* ''Shedding Life: Disease, Politics and Other Human Conditions'' trans. David Young, with assistance by Dana Habova, Todd Morath, Vera Orac, Catarina Vocadlova, and the author (Milkweed Editions, 1997).  {{ISBN|1-57131-217-X}}\n* ''Supposed to Fly'' trans. Ewald Osers (Bloodaxe Books; 1996). {{ISBN|1 85224 274 4}}\n* ''The Fly'' trans. Ewald Osers, George Theiner, Ian & Jarmila Milner (Bloodaxe Books; 1987). {{ISBN|1 85224 018 0}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/1998/07/22/arts/miroslav-holub-is-dead-at-74-czech-poet-and-immunologist.html New York Times obituary]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20040821093632/http://www.arts.gla.ac.uk/Slavonic/Holub.htm Overview of poetic career by Jan Cul\u00edk and Ji\u0159\u00ed Hol\u00fd, in English]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090210044636/http://dogmatika.com/dm/features_more.php?id=3281_0_5_0_M Dogmatika profile of Holub \u2013 Darran Anderson]\n*[http://www.complete-review.com/authors/holubm.htm Miroslav Holub] at the ''[[complete review]]'' \u2013 many further links\n*[http://design.radio.cz/en/article/43324 Brief talk quoting his poem ''Ode to joy'']\n*[http://design.radio.cz/en/article/43324 Biography in Czech]\n*[http://www.svu2000.org/conferences/38.doc Michal Bauer, 'The Portrayal of the United States of Miroslav Holub\u2019s Writing From the 1960s']\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Holub, Miroslav}}\n[[Category:1923 births]]\n[[Category:1998 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Czech poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:Czech male poets]]\n[[Category:Czech medical writers]]\n[[Category:Czech academics]]\n\n[[Category:Czech immunologists]]\n[[Category:People from Plze\u0148]]\n\n\n{{CzechRepublic-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Miloslav Holub}}\n{{More footnotes|date=September 2010}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name             = Miroslav Holub\n| embed            = \n| honorific_prefix = [[MUDr.]]\n| honorific_suffix = [[DrSc.]]\n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| image_upright    = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| pseudonym        = \n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       =  {{Birth date  |1923|9|13}}  \n| birth_place      = [[ Plze\u0148]], [[Czechoslovakia]]\n| death_date       =   {{Death date and age|1998|7|14|1923|9|13}} \n| death_place      = [[Prague]], [[Czech Republic]]\n| resting_place    = \n| occupation       = poet, immunologist\n| language         = [[Czech language|Czech]]\n| nationality      =  [[Czech people|Czech]]\n| citizenship      = \n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = [[Czechoslovak Academy of Sciences]]\n| period           = \n| genre            = <!-- or: | genres = -->\n| subject          = <!-- or: | subjects = -->\n| movement         = \n| notableworks     = <!-- or: | notablework = -->\n| spouse           = <!-- or: | spouses = -->\n| partner          = <!-- or: | partners = -->\n| children         = \n| relatives        = \n| awards           = \n| signature        = \n| signature_alt    = \n| years_active     = 1958\u201396\n| module           = \n| website          = <!-- {{URL|example.org}} -->\n| portaldisp       = <!-- \"on\", \"yes\", \"true\", etc; or omit -->\n}}\n'''Miroslav Holub''' ({{IPA-cs|m\u026ar\u0254slaf \u0266\u0254l\u028ap|pron}}; 13 September 1923 \u2013 14 July 1998) was a [[Czech Republic|Czech]] [[poet]] and [[Immunology|immunologist]].\n\nHolub's work was heavily influenced by his experiences as an [[Immunologist]], writing many poems using his scientific knowledge to poetic effect. His work is almost always un[[rhyme]]d, so lends itself easily to [[translation]]. It has been translated into more than 30 languages and is especially popular in the [[English language|English]]-speaking world. Although one of the most internationally well-known Czech poets, his reputation continues to languish at home.\n\nHolub was born in [[Plze\u0148]].  His first book in Czech was ''Denn\u00ed slu\u017eba'' (1958), which abandoned the somewhat Stalinist bent of poems earlier in the decade (published in magazines).\n\nIn English, he was first published in the ''[[The Observer|Observer]]'' in 1962, and five years later a ''Selected Poems'' appeared in the Penguin Modern European Poets imprint, with an introduction by [[Al Alvarez]] and translations by [[Ian Milner]] and George Theiner. Holub's work was lauded by many, including [[Ted Hughes]] and [[Seamus Heaney]],<ref>The New York Times, 22 July 1998</ref> and his influence is visible in Hughes' collection ''[[Crow (poetry)|Crow]]'' (1970).\n\nIn addition to poetry, Holub wrote many short essays on various aspects of science, particularly biology and medicine (specifically immunology) and life. A collection of these, titled ''The Dimension of the Present Moment,'' is still in print. In the 1960s, he published two books of what he called 'semi-reportage' about extended visits to the United States.\n\nThe [[minor planet]] [[List_of_minor_planets:_7001\u20138000#401|7496 Miroslavholub]], an [[outer main belt asteroid]], is named in his honour.\n\n==Works in translation==\n* ''Vanishing Lung Syndrome,'' trans. David Young and Dana Habova (Oberlin College Press, 1990). {{ISBN|0-932440-52-5}}; (Faber and Faber, 1990). {{ISBN|0-571-14339-3}}\n* ''Intensive Care: Selected and New Poems,'' ed. David Young (Oberlin College Press, 1996). {{ISBN|0-932440-76-2}}\n* ''The Rampage,'' trans. David Young, Dana H\u00e1bov\u00e1, Rebekah Bloyd and the author (Faber and Faber 1997) {{ISBN|0-571-19253-X}}\n* ''Poems Before and After: Collected English Translations'' (Bloodaxe Books; 2nd ed. 2006). {{ISBN|1-85224-747-9}}\n* ''Shedding Life: Disease, Politics and Other Human Conditions'' trans. David Young, with assistance by Dana Habova, Todd Morath, Vera Orac, Catarina Vocadlova, and the author (Milkweed Editions, 1997).  {{ISBN|1-57131-217-X}}\n* ''Supposed to Fly'' trans. Ewald Osers (Bloodaxe Books; 1996). {{ISBN|1 85224 274 4}}\n* ''The Fly'' trans. Ewald Osers, George Theiner, Ian & Jarmila Milner (Bloodaxe Books; 1987). {{ISBN|1 85224 018 0}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/1998/07/22/arts/miroslav-holub-is-dead-at-74-czech-poet-and-immunologist.html New York Times obituary]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20040821093632/http://www.arts.gla.ac.uk/Slavonic/Holub.htm Overview of poetic career by Jan Cul\u00edk and Ji\u0159\u00ed Hol\u00fd, in English]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090210044636/http://dogmatika.com/dm/features_more.php?id=3281_0_5_0_M Dogmatika profile of Holub - Darran Anderson]\n*[http://www.complete-review.com/authors/holubm.htm Miroslav Holub] at the ''[[complete review]]'' - many further links\n*[http://design.radio.cz/en/article/43324 Brief talk quoting his poem ''Ode to joy'']\n*[http://design.radio.cz/en/article/43324 Biography in Czech]\n*[http://www.svu2000.org/conferences/38.doc Michal Bauer, 'The Portrayal of the United States of Miroslav Holub\u2019s Writing From the 1960s']\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Holub, Miroslav}}\n[[Category:1923 births]]\n[[Category:1998 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Czech poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:Czech male poets]]\n[[Category:Czech medical writers]]\n[[Category:Czech academics]]\n\n[[Category:Czech immunologists]]\n[[Category:People from Plze\u0148]]\n\n\n{{CzechRepublic-writer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "MOS:DATEUNIFY audit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miroslav_Holub"}
{"title_page": "Ginger group", "text_new": "{{about||the group of left-wing Canadian Members of Parliament|Ginger Group|the group of Liberal members of the Queensland Legislative Assembly|Ginger Group (Queensland)}}\nA '''ginger group''' is a formal or informal group within an organisation seeking to influence its direction and activity. The term comes from the phrase [[wikt:ginger up|''ginger up'']], meaning to enliven or stimulate. Ginger groups work to alter the organisation's policies, practices, or office-holders, while still supporting its general goals.<ref>{{Cite book|author=Schur, Norman W. |year=2013 |title=British English A to Zed: A Definitive Guide to the Queen's English |location=New York |publisher=Skyhorse Publishing |page=152 |isbn=978-1-62087-577-3}}</ref> Ginger groups sometimes form within the political parties of [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] countries such as the [[United Kingdom]], [[Canada]], [[Australia]], [[New Zealand]], [[India]], and [[Pakistan]].<ref>{{Cite book|author=Lok Sabha Secretariat |year=1975|title=Glossary of Idioms, English-Hindi: Containing Idioms, Phrases, and Proverbial Sayings Under Letters A to Z |location=New Delhi |publisher=Lok Sabha Secretariat |page=98 |oclc=2540350}}</ref>\n\n== Examples ==\n\n* [[Ginger Group]], a radical group of left-wing Canadian MPs in the 1920s and early 1930s\n* [[Ginger Group (Queensland)]]\n* [[Kitchen Cabinet]], a term used by political opponents of [[President of the United States]] [[Andrew Jackson]] to describe his ginger group\n* [[League of Empire Loyalists]], a 1950s UK ginger group\n* [[Momentum (organisation)|Momentum]], which has been described as a ginger group<ref>{{cite web|last=Ley |first=Shaun |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-34941888 |title=Deselection fear hangs over Corbyn's critics - BBC News |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=2015-11-30 |accessdate=2019-09-05}}</ref> within the British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]]\n\n== See also ==\n\n*[[Entryism]], a more militant tactic not always supporting general goals\n*[[Pressure group]], an outside, as opposed to inside, group formed to influence the direction and activity of an organisation\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ginger Group}}\n[[Category:Political terminology]]\n\n\n{{Poli-term-stub}}\n{{Organization-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{for2|the group of left-wing Canadian Members of Parliament|[[Ginger Group]]|the group of Liberal members of the Queensland Legislative Assembly|[[Ginger Group (Queensland)]]}}\nA '''ginger group''' is a formal or informal group within an organisation seeking to influence its direction and activity. The term comes from the phrase [[wikt:ginger up|''ginger up'']], meaning to enliven or stimulate. Ginger groups work to alter the organisation's policies, practices, or office-holders, while still supporting its general goals.<ref>{{Cite book|author=Schur, Norman W. |year=2013 |title=British English A to Zed: A Definitive Guide to the Queen's English |location=New York |publisher=Skyhorse Publishing |page=152 |isbn=978-1-62087-577-3}}</ref> Ginger groups sometimes form within the political parties of [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] countries such as the [[United Kingdom]], [[Canada]], [[Australia]], [[New Zealand]], [[India]], and [[Pakistan]].<ref>{{Cite book|author=Lok Sabha Secretariat |year=1975|title=Glossary of Idioms, English-Hindi: Containing Idioms, Phrases, and Proverbial Sayings Under Letters A to Z |location=New Delhi |publisher=Lok Sabha Secretariat |page=98 |oclc=2540350}}</ref>\n\n== Examples ==\n\n* [[Ginger Group]], a radical group of left-wing Canadian MPs in the 1920s and early 1930s\n* [[Ginger Group (Queensland)]]\n* [[Kitchen Cabinet]], a term used by political opponents of [[President of the United States]] [[Andrew Jackson]] to describe his ginger group\n* [[League of Empire Loyalists]], a 1950s UK ginger group\n* [[Momentum (organisation)|Momentum]], which has been described as a ginger group<ref>{{cite web|last=Ley |first=Shaun |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-34941888 |title=Deselection fear hangs over Corbyn's critics - BBC News |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=2015-11-30 |accessdate=2019-09-05}}</ref> within the British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]]\n\n== See also ==\n\n*[[Entryism]], a more militant tactic not always supporting general goals\n*[[Pressure group]], an outside, as opposed to inside, group formed to influence the direction and activity of an organisation\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ginger Group}}\n[[Category:Political terminology]]\n\n\n{{Poli-term-stub}}\n{{Organization-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Nihiltres", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Simplified hatnote syntax", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ginger_group"}
