{"title_page": "Mac Holten", "text_new": "{{Use Australian English|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable]]\n| name = Mac Holten\n| honorific-suffix =  [[Order of St Michael and St George|CMG]]\n| image = MacHolten1969.jpg\n| office = [[Minister for Repatriation]]\n| primeminister = [[John Gorton]]<br/>[[William McMahon]]\n| predecessor = [[Colin McKellar]]\n| successor = [[Reg Bishop]]\n| term_start = 12 November 1969\n| term_end = 5 December 1972\n| constituency_MP2 = [[Division of Indi|Indi]]\n| parliament2 = Australian\n| predecessor2 = [[William Bostock]]\n| successor2 = [[Ewen Cameron (Australian politician)|Ewen Cameron]]\n| term_start2 = 22 November 1958\n| term_end2 = 10 December 1977\n| birth_name = Rendle McNeilage Holten\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|df=yes|1922|3|29}}\n| birth_place = [[Melbourne]], Victoria, Australia\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1996|10|12|1922|3|29}}\n| death_place =\n| spouse =\n| party = [[Australian Country Party (1920)|Country]]\n| relations =\n| children =\n| residence =\n| alma_mater =\n| occupation = Footballer\n| profession =\n| religion =\n| signature =\n| website =\n| footnotes =\n}}\n'''Rendle McNeilage \"Mac\" Holten''' [[Order of St Michael and St George|CMG]] (29 March 1922 \u2013 12 October 1996) was an Australian politician and sportsman. He was a member of the [[Australian Country Party (1920)|Country Party]] and represented the [[Division of Indi]] in the [[Australian House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] from 1958 to 1977. He served as [[Minister for Repatriation]] from 1969 to 1972 in the [[Gorton Government|Gorton]] and [[McMahon Government]]s. Before entering politics he played [[Australian rules football]] for the [[Collingwood Football Club]]\n\n==Early life and sporting career==\n[[File:MacHolten.jpg|thumb|left|Holten as a football player.]]\nHolten was born in Melbourne and educated at [[Scotch College, Melbourne]].<ref name=jh>{{Cite web\n |last       = Howard\n |first      = John\n |authorlink = John Howard\n |title      = Condolences: Holten, Hon. Rendle McNeilage, CMG\n |work       = [[Hansard]]\n |publisher  = [[Parliament of Australia]]\n |date       = 17 October 1996\n |url        = http://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/search/display/display.w3p;query=Id%3A%22chamber%2Fhansardr%2F1996-10-17%2F0001%22\n |accessdate = 17 January 2008\n}}</ref>  He left school at 16 to sell life insurance, but with the outbreak of World War II joined the [[Royal Australian Air Force]] in 1940 as a flying instructor and test pilot.  He retired in 1946 with the rank of [[Flight Lieutenant]] and became a grocer.  He kicked 83 goals in 82 games for [[Collingwood Football Club]] where he played in three losing Preliminary Finals<ref>{{AustralianFootball|ref=mac%2Bholten/6791}}</ref> and was also Vice-Captain of the [[Melbourne Cricket Club]] at one time.  On 1949 he moved to [[Wangaratta, Victoria|Wangaratta]] to coach the [[Wangaratta Football Club]].<ref name=pm>{{Cite web\n |last        = McGauran\n |first       = Peter\n |authorlink  = Peter McGauran\n |title       = Condolences: Holten, Hon. Rendle McNeilage, CMG\n |work        = [[Hansard]]\n |publisher   = [[Parliament of Australia]]\n |date        = 17 October 1996\n |url         = http://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/search/display/display.w3p;query=Id%3A%22chamber%2Fhansardr%2F1996-10-17%2F0004%22\n |accessdate  = 17 January 2008\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110524195342/http://parlinfoweb.aph.gov.au/piweb/view_document.aspx?ID=47914&TABLE=HANSARDR\n |archivedate = 24 May 2011\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\nHolten was elected as the [[National Party of Australia|Country Party]] member for [[Division of Indi|Indi]] in the [[Australian House of Representatives]] from the [[1958 Australian federal election|1958 election]] until his defeat by the [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal]] candidate at the [[1977 Australian federal election|1977 election]].  He was  [[Minister for Veterans' Affairs (Australia)|Minister for Repatriation]] from November 1969 to the [[William McMahon|McMahon]] government's defeat at the  [[1972 Australian federal election|1972 election]].  As minister he introduced bills, ''the Native Members of the Forces Benefits Bill 1972'' and ''the Repatriation (Torres Strait Islanders) Bill 1972'', to abolish discrimination in the level of benefits for [[indigenous Australians]] who had served in World War II.<ref name=jh/><ref name=bs>{{Cite web\n |last        = Scott\n |first       = Bruce\n |authorlink  = Bruce Scott (Australian politician)\n |title       = Condolences: Holten, Hon. Rendle McNeilage, CMG\n |work        = [[Hansard]]\n |publisher   = [[Parliament of Australia]]\n |date        = 17 October 1996\n |url         = http://parlinfoweb.aph.gov.au/piweb/view_document.aspx?ID=47918&TABLE=HANSARDR\n |accessdate  = 17 January 2008\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110524195349/http://parlinfoweb.aph.gov.au/piweb/view_document.aspx?ID=47918&TABLE=HANSARDR\n |archivedate = 24 May 2011\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref><ref name=kb>{{Cite web\n |last        = Beazley\n |first       = Kim\n |authorlink  = Kim Beazley\n |title       = Condolences: Holten, Hon. Rendle McNeilage, CMG\n |work        = [[Hansard]]\n |publisher   = [[Parliament of Australia]]\n |date        = 17 October 1996\n |url         = http://parlinfoweb.aph.gov.au/piweb/view_document.aspx?ID=47906&TABLE=HANSARDR\n |accessdate  = 17 January 2008\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110524195610/http://parlinfoweb.aph.gov.au/piweb/view_document.aspx?ID=47906&TABLE=HANSARDR\n |archivedate = 24 May 2011\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref>\n\n==Later life==\nHolten was [[Administrator of Christmas Island]] from 1980 to 1982. He was appointed a Companion of the  [[Order of St Michael and St George]] for his parliamentary and community service in 1980.  He was survived by his wife, Shirley, and three daughters.<ref name=jh/><ref name=pm/><ref name=tf>{{Cite web\n |last        = Fischer\n |first       = Tim\n |authorlink  = Tim Fischer\n |title       = Condolences: Holten, Hon. Rendle McNeilage, CMG\n |work        = [[Hansard]]\n |publisher   = [[Parliament of Australia]]\n |date        = 17 October 1996\n |url         = http://parlinfoweb.aph.gov.au/piweb/view_document.aspx?ID=47910&TABLE=HANSARDR\n |accessdate  = 17 January 2008\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110524195358/http://parlinfoweb.aph.gov.au/piweb/view_document.aspx?ID=47910&TABLE=HANSARDR\n |archivedate = 24 May 2011\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{AFL Tables|ref=M/Mac_Holten.html}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-off}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Colin McKellar]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title= [[Minister for Veterans' Affairs (Australia)|Minister for Repatriation]] |years=1969\u201372}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Reg Bishop]]}}\n{{S-par|au}}\n{{S-bef| before=[[Bill Bostock]] }}\n{{S-ttl| title=Member for [[Division of Indi|Indi]] | years=1958\u201377 }}\n{{S-aft| after= [[Ewen Cameron (Australian politician)|Ewen Cameron]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Holten, Rendle Mcneilage}}\n[[Category:National Party of Australia members of the Parliament of Australia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian House of Representatives for Indi]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Australian Companions of the Order of St Michael and St George]]\n[[Category:Collingwood Football Club players]]\n[[Category:Wangaratta Football Club players]]\n[[Category:Australian sportsperson-politicians]]\n[[Category:1922 births]]\n[[Category:1996 deaths]]\n[[Category:Christmas Island administrators]]\n[[Category:Melbourne Cricket Club cricketers]]\n[[Category:People educated at Scotch College, Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Australian rules footballers from Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Australian English|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable]]\n| name = Mac Holten\n| honorific-suffix =  [[Order of St Michael and St George|CMG]]\n| image = MacHolten1969.jpg\n| office = [[Minister for Repatriation]]\n| primeminister = [[John Gorton]]<br/>[[William McMahon]]\n| predecessor = [[Colin McKellar]]\n| successor = [[Reg Bishop]]\n| term_start = 12 November 1969\n| term_end = 5 December 1972\n| constituency_MP2 = [[Division of Indi|Indi]]\n| parliament2 = Australian\n| predecessor2 = [[William Bostock]]\n| successor2 = [[Ewen Cameron (Australian politician)|Ewen Cameron]]\n| term_start2 = 22 November 1958\n| term_end2 = 10 December 1977\n| birth_name = Rendle McNeilage Holten\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|df=yes|1922|3|29}}\n| birth_place = [[Melbourne]], Victoria, Australia\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1996|10|12|1922|3|29}}\n| death_place =\n| spouse =\n| party = [[Australian Country Party (1920)|Country]]\n| relations =\n| children =\n| residence =\n| alma_mater =\n| occupation = Footballer\n| profession =\n| religion =\n| signature =\n| website =\n| footnotes =\n}}\n'''Rendle McNeilage \"Mac\" Holten''' [[Order of St Michael and St George|CMG]] (29 March 1922 \u2013 12 October 1996) was an Australian politician and sportsman. He was a member of the [[Australian Country Party (1920)|Country Party]] and represented the [[Division of Indi]] in the [[Australian House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] from 1958 to 1977. He served as [[Minister for Repatriation]] from 1969 to 1972 in the [[Gorton Government|Gorton]] and [[McMahon Government]]s. Before entering politics he played [[Australian rules football]] for the [[Collingwood Football Club]]\n\n==Early life and sporting career==\n[[File:MacHolten.jpg|thumb|left|Holten as a football player.]]\nHolten was born in Melbourne and educated at [[Scotch College, Melbourne]].<ref name=jh>{{Cite web\n |last       = Howard\n |first      = John\n |authorlink = John Howard\n |title      = Condolences: Holten, Hon. Rendle McNeilage, CMG\n |work       = [[Hansard]]\n |publisher  = [[Parliament of Australia]]\n |date       = 17 October 1996\n |url        = http://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/search/display/display.w3p;query=Id%3A%22chamber%2Fhansardr%2F1996-10-17%2F0001%22\n |accessdate = 17 January 2008\n}}</ref>  He left school at 16 to sell life insurance, but with the outbreak of World War II joined the [[Royal Australian Air Force]] in 1940 as a flying instructor and test pilot.  He retired in 1946 with the rank of [[Flight Lieutenant]] and became a grocer.  He kicked 83 goals in 82 games for [[Collingwood Football Club]] where he played in three losing Preliminary Finals<ref>{{AustralianFootball|ref=mac%2Bholten/6791}}</ref> and was also Vice-Captain of the [[Melbourne Cricket Club]] at one time.  On 1949 he moved to [[Wangaratta, Victoria|Wangaratta]] to coach the [[Wangaratta Football Club]].<ref name=pm>{{Cite web\n |last        = McGauran\n |first       = Peter\n |authorlink  = Peter McGauran\n |title       = Condolences: Holten, Hon. Rendle McNeilage, CMG\n |work        = [[Hansard]]\n |publisher   = [[Parliament of Australia]]\n |date        = 17 October 1996\n |url         = http://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/search/display/display.w3p;query=Id%3A%22chamber%2Fhansardr%2F1996-10-17%2F0004%22\n |accessdate  = 17 January 2008\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110524195342/http://parlinfoweb.aph.gov.au/piweb/view_document.aspx?ID=47914&TABLE=HANSARDR\n |archivedate = 24 May 2011\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\nHolten was elected as the [[National Party of Australia|Country Party]] member for [[Division of Indi|Indi]] in the [[Australian House of Representatives]] from the [[1958 Australian federal election|1958 election]] until his defeat by the [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal]] candidate at the [[1977 Australian federal election|1977 election]].  He was  [[Minister for Veterans' Affairs (Australia)|Minister for Repatriation]] from November 1969 to the [[William McMahon|McMahon]] government's defeat at the  [[1972 Australian federal election|1972 election]].  As minister he introduced bills, ''the Native Members of the Forces Benefits Bill 1972'' and ''the Repatriation (Torres Strait Islanders) Bill 1972'', to abolish discrimination in the level of benefits for [[indigenous Australians]] who had served in World War II.<ref name=jh/><ref name=bs>{{Cite web\n |last        = Scott\n |first       = Bruce\n |authorlink  = Bruce Scott (Australian politician)\n |title       = Condolences: Holten, Hon. Rendle McNeilage, CMG\n |work        = [[Hansard]]\n |publisher   = [[Parliament of Australia]]\n |date        = 17 October 1996\n |url         = http://parlinfoweb.aph.gov.au/piweb/view_document.aspx?ID=47918&TABLE=HANSARDR\n |accessdate  = 17 January 2008\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110524195349/http://parlinfoweb.aph.gov.au/piweb/view_document.aspx?ID=47918&TABLE=HANSARDR\n |archivedate = 24 May 2011\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref><ref name=kb>{{Cite web\n |last        = Beazley\n |first       = Kim\n |authorlink  = Kim Beazley\n |title       = Condolences: Holten, Hon. Rendle McNeilage, CMG\n |work        = [[Hansard]]\n |publisher   = [[Parliament of Australia]]\n |date        = 17 October 1996\n |url         = http://parlinfoweb.aph.gov.au/piweb/view_document.aspx?ID=47906&TABLE=HANSARDR\n |accessdate  = 17 January 2008\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110524195610/http://parlinfoweb.aph.gov.au/piweb/view_document.aspx?ID=47906&TABLE=HANSARDR\n |archivedate = 24 May 2011\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref>\n\n==Later life==\nHolten was [[Administrator of Christmas Island]] from 1980 to 1982. He was appointed a Companion of the  [[Order of St Michael and St George]] for his parliamentary and community service in 1980.  He was survived by his wife, Shirley, and three daughters.<ref name=jh/><ref name=pm/><ref name=tf>{{Cite web\n |last        = Fischer\n |first       = Tim\n |authorlink  = Tim Fischer\n |title       = Condolences: Holten, Hon. Rendle McNeilage, CMG\n |work        = [[Hansard]]\n |publisher   = [[Parliament of Australia]]\n |date        = 17 October 1996\n |url         = http://parlinfoweb.aph.gov.au/piweb/view_document.aspx?ID=47910&TABLE=HANSARDR\n |accessdate  = 17 January 2008\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110524195358/http://parlinfoweb.aph.gov.au/piweb/view_document.aspx?ID=47910&TABLE=HANSARDR\n |archivedate = 24 May 2011\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{AFL Tables|ref=M/Mac_Holten.html}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-off}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Colin McKellar]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title= [[Minister for Veterans' Affairs (Australia)|Minister for Repatriation]] |years=1969\u201372}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Reg Bishop]]}}\n{{S-par|au}}\n{{S-bef| before=[[Bill Bostock]] }}\n{{S-ttl| title=Member for [[Division of Indi|Indi]] | years=1958\u201377 }}\n{{S-aft| after= [[Ewen Cameron (Australian politician)|Ewen Cameron]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Holten, Rendle Mcneilage}}\n[[Category:National Party of Australia members of the Parliament of Australia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian House of Representatives for Indi]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Australian Companions of the Order of St Michael and St George]]\n[[Category:Collingwood Football Club players]]\n[[Category:Wangaratta Football Club players]]\n[[Category:Australian sportsperson-politicians]]\n[[Category:1922 births]]\n[[Category:1996 deaths]]\n[[Category:Christmas I